---
description: FastAPI backend rules
globs: backend/**, app/**.py
---

Backend stack:
- Python 3.12
- FastAPI (async)
- SQLAlchemy 2.0 + AsyncPG for PostgreSQL persistence
- Alembic for database migrations
- Pydantic v2 for validation and schemas
- Redis for cache, pub/sub, and Celery broker
- Celery for async AI processing tasks (transcription, analysis, deal prediction)
- python-socketio for real-time WebSocket events
- OpenAI API (GPT-4o for analysis, Whisper for STT)
- Twilio Voice SDK for telephony and media streams
- JWT-based auth with refresh tokens

Backend rules:
- Use clean architecture.
- Routes/controllers should only handle HTTP/WebSocket concerns.
- Business logic must live in services (call analysis, transcription, deal prediction, lead management).
- Database access must live in repositories or use SQLAlchemy session patterns.
- Validation must be done using Pydantic schemas/models.
- Use dependency injection patterns (FastAPI Depends).
- Use async I/O for external calls (OpenAI, Twilio, Redis).
- Use pagination for list endpoints.
- Use consistent response models.
- Use centralized exception handling.

API conventions:
- Follow RESTful naming; version APIs (e.g. /api/v1/).
- Use proper status codes; return predictable response structure.
- Do not leak internal stack traces or raw database errors.
- Support WebSocket via Socket.IO for real-time call features.

Existing backend structure (do not reorganize):
- backend/app/api/routes/          (HTTP routes)
- backend/app/api/dependencies/
- backend/app/services/            (business logic: calls, analysis, prediction, leads)
- backend/app/models/              (SQLAlchemy ORM models)
- backend/app/schemas/             (Pydantic request/response schemas)
- backend/app/core/                (config, security, logging)
- backend/app/realtime/            (Socket.IO + Twilio media stream handlers)
- backend/app/tasks/               (Celery async tasks)
- backend/app/utils/
- backend/tests/

Do not:
- Put SQL or ORM-heavy logic inside route files.
- Put business logic inside Pydantic schemas.
- Put environment variables directly across many files; centralize in app/config.py.
- Mix unrelated domains in the same service file.
- Hardcode Twilio credentials, OpenAI keys, or database URLs; use config/env.
